SIMPLE: staddle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Staddle
<hw>Stad"dle</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧d"d'l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sta⟦edh⟧ol</ets>, <ets>sta⟦edh⟧ul</ets>, a foundation, firm seat;
akin to E. <ets>stand</ets>. ⟦root⟧163. See <er>Stand</er>, <pos>v.
i.</pos>]</ety> <altsp>[Formerly written <asp>stadle</asp>.]</altsp>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Anything which serves for support; a staff; a prop; a
crutch; a cane.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His weak steps governing⟦br⟧
And aged limbs on cypress <qex>stadle</qex> stout.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The frame of a stack of hay or grain.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A row of dried or drying hay, etc.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small tree of any kind, especially a forest
tree.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In America, trees are called <xex>staddles</xex> from
the time that they are three or four years old till they are six or
eight inches in diameter, or more. This is also the sense in which the
word is used by Bacon and Tusser.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Staddle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Staddle
<hw>Stad"dle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To leave the
staddles, or saplings, of, as a wood when it is cut.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Tusser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To form into staddles, as hay.</def>
<mark>[Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stade</ent>⟦br⟧
